t5009.text: People see the flattening but that just may be the incubation period between limiting OS arrivals, and our own curve taking off. Finally. Good luck. Sanitise. Stay separated.

t5010.text: In Aust there are going to be two (or more) phases of spread. We’ve seen the early spread where most cases were from OS. Now we’ve moved into the society spread. And the two graphs are actually different. My fear is complacency.

t5011.text: Had those milder cases not been highlighted and then tested, our initial figures would have been much lower. In Italy, there would have been far bigger numbers infected early than were tested. A blip down like we’re having now, in the early phase, is most likely illusory.

t5013.text: It’s possible our initial high rate of positive tests reflects a selection bias. Also if we were able to scramble together lots of mild cases initially because of the above reasons, then that makes our graph now look flatter.

t5014.text: In Australia’s case, the initial weeks involved clumps spread by defined events: Dutton’s flight. The Aspen idiots convention. The Ruby Princess. Tom ‘Castaway’ Hanks. While it was silently spreading we were able to focus in specific regions and pick up a lot of cases.

t5015.text: Shit that’s risky.. not worth the fine!

t5016.text: My thought, for what it’s worth. Australia’s trend is welcome. But we’re different from all other countries. Geographically isolated. Limited ports of entry. As with all countries bar China #CONVID19 came over our borders.

t5018.text: And lastly, call out the BS where you can - but if it’s coming from someone potentially uninformed or from a “good place”, be kind in doing so. If it’s coming from a place of fear mongering or publicity, that’s another story. (8/8)
